"1179.","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","before 1160":"prije 1160.","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"cs":{"before 1160–":"před 1160–Zesnulá","1160–Female":"1160–Zesnulá","1154–Male":"1154–Zesnulý","1179–Female":"1179–Zesnulá","1101–Male":"1101–Zesnulý","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","before 1160":"před 1160","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"before 1160–":"før 1160–Afdød","1160–Female":"1160–Afdød","1154–Male":"1154–Afdød","1179–Female":"1179–Afdød","1101–Male":"1101–Afdød","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","before 1160":"før 1160","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"nl":{"before 1160–":"vóór 1160–Overleden","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1154–Male":"1154–Overleden","1179–Female":"1179–Overleden","1101–Male":"1101–Overleden","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","before 1160":"vóór 1160","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"before 1160–":"before 1160–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1154–Male":"1154–Deceased","1179–Female":"1179–Deceased","1101–Male":"1101–Deceased","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","before 1160":"before 1160","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzGerold","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, Liam, Aidan, Bridgid, Caitlin, Donal, Fitz, Fitzgerald, Ciaran, Colum, Dermot.","Irish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name <i>Gerald</i> (see   Gerald  ), ‘son of <i>Gerald</i>’. This is a very common Anglo-Norman name in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>Mac Gearailt</b>. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from <i>Gerald</i> Fitzwalter de Windsor, constable of Pembroke Castle in the early 12th century, whose grandson Raymond (or Redmond) ‘le Gros’ <i>FitzGerald</i> (died after 1185) led the invasion of Ireland on behalf of Strongbow in 1170. A branch of the family held the title Knight of Glin from at least 1299–2011."],"variants":[{"name":"Jarrell","meanings":["Irish: altered form of   Fitzgerald  .","English (Kent and Middlesex; of Norman origin): variant of <b>Jarrold</b>, itself a variant of   Gerald  ."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":64,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":99,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret FitzGerold was born before 1160, in England, her father, Caballero Ballon, was 58 and her mother, Adelize Ballon, was 60. She had at least 1 daughter with Faulk de Braie."},"et":{"before 1160–":"enne 1160–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1101–Male":"1101–Surnud","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","before 1160":"enne 1160","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"before 1160–":"ennen vuotta 1160–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1154–Male":"1154–Kuollut","1179–Female":"1179–Kuollut","1101–Male":"1101–Kuollut","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","